In the early 19th Century, there was tented accomodation for the armies of the Dukes of York and Cambridge, on Bagshot Heath. As these became permanent, the areas were named {Yorktown}and{Cambridge Town.}
In 1812 the Military Academy was moved from Woolwich to Sandhurst, Cambridge Town, and in the 1870s, the{railway} came to Cambridge Town, improving communications and leading to a large increase in the volume of mail.
The{Royal Mail}confused Cambridge Town with Cambridge and at their insistence, the former changed its name to Camberley. Yorktown is still so called.
